INSERT INTO news_stories (id, record_id, url, body_text, ai_summary) VALUES ('d29e65e5-352e-4c6e-a5ab-d189e701d31c', '43eddaf8-51a9-4394-bd48-2267aadb9f6d', 'https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/father-charged-in-aurora-triple-murder-1.581712', 'ContentSkip to Main ContentAccessibility HelpMenuWhen search suggestions are available use up and down arrows to review and enter to select.SearchSearchSign InQuick LinksNewsSportsRadioMusicListen LiveTVWatchnewsTop StoriesLocalClimateWorldCanadaPoliticsIndigenousOpinionThe NationalBusinessHealthEntertainmentScienceCBC News InvestigatesGo PublicAbout CBC NewsBeing Black in CanadaMore Father charged in Aurora triple murder | CBC News LoadedTorontoFather charged in Aurora triple murderPolice have charged an Aurora father with three counts of first-degree murder after the death of his estranged wife and two young children in their home early Sunday.CBC News  · Posted: Mar 06, 2006 3:31 PM EST | Last Updated: March 6, 2006Police have charged an Aurora father with three counts of first-degree murder after the death of his estranged wife and two young children in their home early Sunday.                                                                           Wendy LaFleche                                                     VIDEO:                                                     James Murray reports (runs 02:24)                  RP WP  QT                                                  Wendy LaFleche, 41, was found dead, along with her seven-year-old daughter Victoria, and three-year-old son Jesse.  The cause of death was not revealed during a media briefing held Monday by York Regional Police. The autopsies must be completed first.  Police were called to the modest home on Yonge Street and arrived to find the front door open and toys scattered on the floor. They arrested the woman&#39;s estranged husband John LaFleche, 41, following a 30-minute high speed chase that ended in Barrie. Speeds reportedly reached 180 kmph. A third child from LaFleche&#39;s first marriage – 16-year-old Devon – was not at home at the time of the murders. He lived with his mom but was staying at a friend&#39;s house that night. &#34;My understanding is the boy is in the care of friends and relatives now,&#34; said York Regional Police Chief Armand LaBarge. People who knew the mother said the degree of violence was unexpected although LaFleche had recently split with her husband after several rocky years. LaFleche worked as a hairdresser in Aurora. A co-worker who saw LaFleche the day before said her friend did not appear agitated and was joking and laughing as normal, according to newspaper reports. A former client said he couldn&#39;t believe what had happened. &#34;She wasn&#39;t the type of person to have any problems that you&#39;d know of,&#34; said Randy Gilpin, who used to bring his son to LaFleche for haircuts. &#34;It would make anybody feel devastated, specially when you have young children. A small town like Aurora, you wouldn&#39;t expect it to happen anyways,&#34; said Gilpin. People in the town came to the scene of the murder through the day Sunday, out of interest and to pay their respects. Others met and wept at the salon where she worked. FROM FEB. 10, 2006: Toronto triple murder suspect makes court appearance  FROM MARCH 3, 2006: Mom charged after girls killed in Markham home   This is the third disturbing case of domestic violence in which a parent has been accused of killing a child.  Late last week, a toddler and an infant were discovered dead in their Markham home. Their mother has been charged with first-degree murder in both deaths. Two weeks earlier, a Scarborough father was charged in the triple murder of his wife and two young children, aged three years, and five months. CBC&#39;s Journalistic Standards and Practices|About CBC NewsCorrections and clarifications|Submit a news tip|Report errorFooter LinksMy AccountProfileCBC GemNewslettersAbout CBC AccountsConnect with CBCFacebookTwitterYouTubeInstagramMobileRSSPodcastsContact CBCSubmit FeedbackHelp CentreAudience Relations, CBC P.O. Box 500 Station A Toronto, ON  Canada, M5W 1E6 Toll-free (Canada only):  1-866-306-4636About CBCCorporate InfoSitemapReuse &amp; PermissionTerms of UsePrivacyJobsOur UnionsIndependent ProducersPolitical Ads RegistryAdChoicesServicesOmbudsmanCorrections and ClarificationsPublic AppearancesCommercial ServicesCBC ShopDoing Business with UsRenting FacilitiesRadio Canada InternationalCBC LiteAccessibilityIt is a priority for CBC to create products that are accessible to all in Canada including people with visual, hearing, motor and cognitive challenges.Closed Captioning and Described Video is available for many CBC shows offered on CBC Gem.About CBC AccessibilityAccessibility Feedback©2023 CBC/Radio-Canada. All rights reserved. Visitez Radio-Canada.canow', NULL);
