INSERT INTO news_stories (id, record_id, url, body_text, ai_summary) VALUES ('ff6ee395-1038-4952-9d18-db9ff4a586e5', 'e9ee77e5-f3ec-42d8-b7b9-475143a95799', 'https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/two-accused-in-shooting-death-of-jordan-manners-acquitted/article598148/', 'Skip to main contentAdChoicesCanadaWorldBusinessInvestingWatchlistPersonal FinanceOpinionPoliticsSportsLifeArtsDriveReal EstatePodcastsTwo accused in shooting death of Jordan Manners acquittedTimothy ApplebyTorontoPublished May 19, 2011This article was published more than 12 years ago. Some information may no longer be current.Loreen Small, the mother of Jordan Manners who was murdered at CW Jeffreys school, leaves the courthouse at 361 University Avenue in Toronto, Ont. March 21/2011.Kevin Van Paassen/The Globe and MailShareCries of surprise and elation rang out in a downtown Toronto courtroom as two young men charged with first-degree murder in the shooting death of Toronto teenager Jordan Manners were acquitted and walked free after four years in custody.The jury delivered its verdict on Thursday afternoon after less than 12 hours of deliberations during the second trial of the two accused. Few had expected it so soon. Amid a torrent of emotion in the packed courtroom, the defendants hugged their lawyers before making their exit, avoiding the media throng that gathered outside.The jury&#39;s verdict came one day after what would have been Jordan&#39;s 19th birthday, and his aunt, Ramona Manners, greeted it with dismay.&#34;We&#39;re really upset, how do you expect us to feel as a family?&#34; she said. &#34;I judge nobody. God will judge them.&#34;There will be no appeal, the lead prosecutor said afterward.Both the defendants, known as C.D. and J.W., are 21, but neither can be identified because they were 17 when the Grade 9 student was shot and killed at C.W. Jefferys Collegiate Institute in North York in May, 2007.The trial drew wide attention, not only because Jordan&#39;s death - the first fatal shooting in a Toronto school - became an emblem of urban gun violence among young people, but because the first trial was aborted last year when the jury was unable to reach consensus.In large part, the Crown&#39;s case rested on a statement to police - later retracted - by a teenage girl who offered conflicting stories at the two trials. Lawyer Gary Grill, co-counsel for C.D., suggested her uncertainty was pivotal to the defence victory.&#34;That original statement to the police made no sense, it had a robbery, a shot with no sound and no gun evidence, and Mr. Manners wasn&#39;t missing anything of value,&#34; he said.&#34;I think [the witness]was an accomplished liar, even at a very young age, she was good at it.&#34;Jordan was found dying by a ground-floor stairway, killed by a .25-calibre bullet to the heart. But neither the gun nor the shell casing was ever located, there was no physical evidence against either accused, and at both trials, it was clear that potential witnesses were too frightened to testify.The homicide detective who headed the investigation, Det. Sgt. Mike Barsky, said the key prosecution witness who retracted her original statement, and another witness, &#34;hijacked the process by changing their testimony so drastically.&#34;Absent from the tense proceedings as the verdict was delivered was Jordan&#39;s mother, Loreen Small, who had been present earlier in the day and during some testimony.But on the other side of the courtroom, relatives and friends of the defendants cheered, despite being warned not to do so by Superior Court Justice John McMahon, and a woman who gave a loud shout was ordered out of the courtroom.Both trials hinged on a tangle of competing testimony, and as the jurors began their second day of deliberations on Thursday morning, it became evident that they were sharpening their focus. They asked to review two videoed statements given to police a few hours after Jordan died.One of those accounts came from the young woman cited as unreliable by Mr. Grill. She initially told detectives she saw J.W. drag Jordan down a flight of stairs, put something to his chest that could have been a gun but made no sound, and configure his body to make it appear he had fallen.Then, she said, co-defendant C.D. robbed the dying boy of a wallet, cellphone and neck chain.But the girl later recanted, telling both trials she had lied. And there was never any proof that Jordan, 15, had in fact been robbed, since his valuables were still in his pockets when his body was examined in hospital.Meanwhile, a second teen-aged girl gave police an alternate eyewitness version of events, which the defence used to suggest that Jordan and two other unidentified boys had been in a second floor washroom examining a .25-calibre handgun that had accidentally discharged.J.W., the alleged shooter, testified at his second trial, which his co-counsel Donald McLeod said later may have helped steer the jury away from the &#34;tunnel vision&#34; he suggested had marred the police investigation.&#34;This was the first time that a jury was able to hear an account right from one of the accused, the veracity of his testimony went unchallenged, he was able to stand up under cross-examination and the evidence he gave was consistent,&#34; Mr. McLeod said.Clearly disappointed at the outcome, prosecutor Tom Lissaman nonetheless said the verdict was reasonable and would not be appealed.&#34;This was a very difficult case for the prosecution, we respect the verdict of the jury and our hearts go out to the Manners family, particularly Jordan&#39;s mother,&#34; he said.The two defendants - both friends of Jordan, according to trial testimony - have also paid a high price, said C.D&#39;s co-counsel, James Silver, noting that his client has a young child he barely knows because he spent years behind bars awaiting trial.&#34;This is a tragedy that cost Jordan Manners his life and cost these boys four years of their lives,&#34; he told reporters outside the courthouse.&#34;They lost their friend. What are they going to do now? They are going to try and put their lives back together and move forward.&#34;Jordan&#39;s death led to the commissioning of a report on violence in schools. The 2008 Falconer report concluded that there are firearms and weapons in &#34;non-trivial&#34; numbers at some Toronto schools. The findings of the report contributed to the formation of the School Resource Officer program which placed Toronto police officers in some schools around the city.With a report from Tim AlamenciakFollow us on Twitter: @globetorontoOpens in a new windowReport an errorEditorial code of conductTerms &amp; ConditionsCommunity GuidelinesPrivacy PolicyDisclaimerSkip footer navigationSubscribeDigital + Home DeliveryDigital AccessGlobe2GoThe New York TimesGlobe Email NewslettersGift SubscriptionBusiness servicesAdvertise with UsGroup SubscriptionsGlobe CampusContent LicensingDataStoreReport On Business Top 1000Globe Event CentreSophi.ioContact usAddress and Phone NumberPublic EditorStaffStaff PGP DirectorySecureDropSubmit an articleReader servicesMy globeandmail.com AccountTechnical Support &amp; FAQsManage my home deliveryManage my privacy preferencesManage my advertising preferencesMember BenefitsAbout usCompany informationWork at The GlobeAccessibilityEditorial Code of ConductSustainabilityLicensing &amp; PermissionsElection Advertising RegistrySubscribeDigital + Home DeliveryDigital AccessGlobe2GoThe New York TimesGlobe Email NewslettersGift SubscriptionBusiness servicesAdvertise with UsGroup SubscriptionsGlobe CampusContent LicensingDataStoreReport On Business Top 1000Globe Event CentreSophi.ioContact usAddress and Phone NumberPublic EditorStaffStaff PGP DirectorySecureDropSubmit an articleReader servicesMy globeandmail.com AccountTechnical Support &amp; FAQsManage my home deliveryManage my privacy preferencesManage my advertising preferencesMember BenefitsAbout usCompany informationWork at The GlobeAccessibilityEditorial Code of ConductSustainabilityLicensing &amp; PermissionsElection Advertising RegistryReturn to start of footer navigation© Copyright 2023 The Globe and Mail Inc. All rights reserved.351 King Street East, Suite 1600, Toronto, ON Canada, M5A 0N1Phillip Crawley, Publisher', NULL);
